{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":2992417,"name":"Ethan Hanlon","username":"OccultSlolem","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/o/8491ac/{size}.png","created_at":"2022-01-15T22:30:08.857Z","cooked":"<p>Hey all, I’m trying to do some unit testing with the command-based framework, and I’m finding that I can test subsystems just fine, but commands don’t really want to work. Consider this subsystem:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-java">public class ExampleSystem extends SubsystemBase {
    private CANSparkMax spark;

    public ExampleSubsystem() {
        spark = new CANSparkMax(0, MotorType.kBrushless);
    }

    public void run() {
        spark.set(0.3);
    }

    public void close() {
        spark.close();
    }

    public double getSpeedPercentage() {
        return spark.get();
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>And this command:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public class RunCommand extends CommandBase {
    private ExampleSubsystem subsystem;

    public RunCommand(ExampleSubsystem subsystem) {
        this.subsystem = subsystem;
        addRequirements(subsystem);
    }

    @Override
    public void execute() {
        subsystem.run();
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Simple enough. However, the tests don’t seem to think so:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public class SubsystemTests {
    private static double delta = 1e-3; // 0.01
    ExampleSubsystem subsystem;

    @Before
    public void setup() {
        subsystem = new ExampleSubsystem();
    }

    @After
    public void shutdown() {
        subsystem.close();

    @Test // This test PASSES
    public void testSubsystem() {
        subsystem.run();
        assertEquals(0.3, subsystem.getSpeedPercentage(), delta);
    }

    @Test // This test FAILS
    public void testCommand() {
        RunCommand command = new RunCommand(subsystem);
        CommandScheduler scheduler = CommandScheduler.getInstance();

        scheduler.schedule(command);
        scheduler.run();

        assertEquals(0.3, subsystem.getSpeedPercentage(), delta);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>As I mention in the comments, the subsystem test passes while the command test fails. Am I doing something wrong with the CommandScheduler?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2022-01-15T22:32:59.148Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":129,"reads":82,"readers_count":81,"score":661.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":400367,"topic_slug":"trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java","display_username":"Ethan Hanlon","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":50780,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java/400367/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":2992427,"name":"Bart Kerfeld","username":"Bart_Kerfeld","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bart_kerfeld/{size}/156555_2.png","created_at":"2022-01-15T22:43:15.401Z","cooked":"<p>Are you certain your test is importing the correct <code>RunCommand</code>? WPILIB includes its own <a href="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibNewCommands/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj2/command/RunCommand.java" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">RunCommand</a> class. I suspect your test is importing the WPILIB version instead of the one you have written.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2022-01-15T22:43:15.401Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":67,"readers_count":66,"score":18.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":400367,"topic_slug":"trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java","display_username":"Bart Kerfeld","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibNewCommands/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj2/command/RunCommand.java","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":4}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":19314,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java/400367/2","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2992428,"name":"Ethan Hanlon","username":"OccultSlolem","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/o/8491ac/{size}.png","created_at":"2022-01-15T22:44:26.262Z","cooked":"<p>Looking at my imports, I am importing the <code>RunCommand</code> from my own code and not WPIlib’s.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2022-01-15T22:44:26.262Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":67,"readers_count":66,"score":18.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":400367,"topic_slug":"trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java","display_username":"Ethan Hanlon","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":19314,"username":"Bart_Kerfeld","name":"Bart Kerfeld","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bart_kerfeld/{size}/156555_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":50780,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java/400367/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2992433,"name":"Bart Kerfeld","username":"Bart_Kerfeld","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bart_kerfeld/{size}/156555_2.png","created_at":"2022-01-15T22:51:31.908Z","cooked":"<p>Okay. I’m looking through the CommandScheduler implementation. I wonder if you might be hitting <a href="https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibNewCommands/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj2/command/CommandScheduler.java#L174" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">this case</a> .</p>
<p>Can you try enabling the CommandScheduler using the <code>enable()</code> method? For example:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    @Test
    public void testCommand() {
        RunCommand command = new RunCommand(subsystem);
        CommandScheduler scheduler = CommandScheduler.getInstance();
        scheduler.enable(); // Add this line.

        scheduler.schedule(command);
        scheduler.run();

        assertEquals(0.3, subsystem.getSpeedPercentage(), delta);
    }
</code></pre>
<p>If that still doesn’t work. Let’s see if we can try to find a way to verify the command is in fact being scheduled.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2022-01-15T22:52:37.480Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":64,"readers_count":63,"score":22.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":400367,"topic_slug":"trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java","display_username":"Bart Kerfeld","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibNewCommands/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj2/command/CommandScheduler.java#L174","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":5}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":19314,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java/400367/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2992434,"name":"Ethan Hanlon","username":"OccultSlolem","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/o/8491ac/{size}.png","created_at":"2022-01-15T22:54:42.056Z","cooked":"<p>I was just looking through the API and I just noticed the enable method myself. I tried it as you said, but it made no difference <img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/confused.png?v=9" title=":confused:" class="emoji" alt=":confused:"></p>
<p>Something I tried was printing the result of <code>scheduler.isScheduled()</code> on the command, which resulted in false regardless of where I put it:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    @Test
    public void testCommand() {
        RunCommand command = new RunCommand(subsystem);
        CommandScheduler scheduler = CommandScheduler.getInstance();
        scheduler.enable();

        scheduler.schedule(command);
        System.out.println(scheduler.isScheduled(command)); // &gt;false
        scheduler.run();
        System.out.println(scheduler.isScheduled(command)); // &gt;false

        assertEquals(0.3, subsystem.getSpeedPercentage(), delta);
    }
</code></pre>
<p>I’m not entirely sure what’s preventing it from going into the scheduler. If there’s some runtime error happening, it’s not being printed to the console and running <code>./gradlew test --info</code> or <code>./gradlew test --stacktrace</code> isn’t revealing it.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":12,"updated_at":"2022-01-15T22:57:29.378Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":2,"reads":57,"readers_count":56,"score":26.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":400367,"topic_slug":"trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java","display_username":"Ethan Hanlon","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":19314,"username":"Bart_Kerfeld","name":"Bart Kerfeld","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bart_kerfeld/{size}/156555_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":50780,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/trouble-unit-testing-commands-in-java/400367/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2992438,"name":"Bart Kerfeld","username":"Bart_Kerfeld","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bart_kerfeld/{size}/156555_2.png","created_at":"2022-01-15T23:03:18.178Z","cooked":"<p>Just on principal of wanting to figure out why it doesn’t work, I’ll keep digging. However, I want to call out that you can do this without the CommandScheduler at all:</p>
